Sure, I can provide you with a basic Discord bot code using Discord.js version 14. In this code, the bot will have one command: the `ban` command. This command will ban the user who invoked it from the current channel. 

Here's a step-by-step guide to help you set up this bot:

1. **Install Node.js and npm**: You'll need Node.js and npm to run JavaScript code. You can download them from the official websites: [Node.js](https://nodejs.org/en/download/) and [npm](https://npm.dev/).

2. **Create a new JavaScript file**: Open your preferred text editor or Integrated Development Environment (IDE). Copy and paste the following code into the editor:

```javascript
const Discord = require('discord.js');
const client = new Discord.Client();

client.once('ready', () => {
    console.log('Bot is ready!');
});

client.on('message', (message) => {
    if (message.content.startsWith('!ban')) {
        const userId = message.author.id;
        client.channels.cache.get('your-channel-id').send(`You've been banned by ${userId}`);
        client.ban(userId, 'Banned by another user');
    }
});

client.login('your-token');
```

3. **Replace 'your-token' with your Discord bot token**: Your bot token can be found in the Discord developer portal under "Token" in your application settings. It's a string of numbers and letters, and it should look something like `your_token://your_username.discordapp.com/api/v14/guilds/your_guild_id/emojis/new`.

4. **Save the file with an `.js` extension**: The file extension for JavaScript files is `.js`. Save the file with this extension, and it should work.

5. **Run the file with Node.js**: Open a terminal or command prompt and use the `node` command to run your JavaScript file. You can do this by typing `node your_file_name.js`.

6. **Test the bot**: Join the channel in which you want to test the bot, type `!ban`, and see if the bot responds correctly.

**Note**: Always be sure to replace 'your-channel-id' with the actual ID of the channel where you want the bot to operate. You can find this ID by looking at the URL of the channel in Discord. It will look something like `https://discordapp.com/channels/your-guild-id/your-channel-name`. The ID is the string of numbers at the end of the URL.

